    <title>Disentangling condensate clouds with contemporaneous IGRINS and TESS monitoring</title>
    <abstract>Condensate clouds on brown dwarfs remain one of the largest unsolved problems in substellar evolution.  The rapid clearing of clouds might control the unusually fast L-T Transition.  Here we propose contemporaneous monitoring of an L-T transition binary, with IGRINS and TESS.  Luhman 16AB is the Sun's third closest neighbor and by far the best laboratory for understanding clouds.  With at least 5 epochs of IGRINS from March 8 - 18, 2021, we can faithfully disambiguate the component A, the cloud-free surface of B, and the clouds on B.  This TESS-coordinated dataset will possess tremendous legacy value for decades, and stands to catalyze a major step forward for the physical chemistry and atmospheric dynamics of clouds on brown dwarfs and large exoplanets.</abstract>
    <scheduling>Must be observed March 8 - March 18, 2021 to coordindate with TESS monitoring.  Five nights of visits at any time in that window, with the preference for a second re-visit within the night, for three of those five nights.</scheduling>
